          "text": "## Summary\n\nI've successfully identified the Grafana alert evaluation scheduler code and the mechanism for detecting evaluation cycle overruns. Here's what I found:\n\n### Key Files:\n1. **pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/schedule.go** - Main scheduler implementation\n2. **pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/ticker/ticker.go** - Ticker that emits evaluation cycles\n3. **pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/alert_rule.go** - Alert rule evaluation handler\n4. **pkg/services/ngalert/metrics/scheduler.go** - Scheduler metrics definitions\n\n### Detection Mechanism:\n\n**Scheduler Tick Loop** (`schedulePeriodic`, line 246):\n- Receives ticks from the ticker and measures latency with `BehindSeconds` metric\n- Tracks iteration duration with `SchedulePeriodicDuration` metric\n\n**Evaluation Cycle Overrun Detection** (`runJobFn`, line 438):\n- When sending an evaluation to a rule, the scheduler checks if a previous evaluation is still pending\n- If a new tick arrives before the previous evaluation completes, the method detects it and logs:\n  ```\n  \"Tick dropped because alert rule evaluation is too slow\"\n  ```\n- Increments `EvaluationMissed` counter to track missed evaluation cycles\n\n**Detection Implementation** (`alertRule.Eval`, lines 200-217):\n- Uses non-blocking channel read to detect if an evaluation message is already waiting\n- Returns the dropped message to the scheduler, signaling an overrun\n\nThe answer has been written to `/workspace/answer.json` with all files, symbols, and the execution chain documented.",
